name: tris(3-methoxyphenyl)phosphine
Reason: 3-methoxyphenyl groups, when connected to a phosphine, increase the melting point due to the enhancement of the crystalline structure and the increase in molecular weight. Each methoxy group introduces additional rigidity and hydrogen bonding potential, estimated at around +10°C. The phosphine moiety itself also contributes to the melting point due to its ability to form hydrogen bonds, estimated at around +20°C. The presence of three methoxyphenyl groups can raise the melting point by approximately +30°C due to the increase in molecular weight and rigidity of the structure.
